\pard\f0\fs28 {\b T. tymphaeum} Hausskn.,{\i  Mitt. Thür. Bot. Ver.}{\b  3-4}:115 (1893) ({\i T. pindicum} Hausskn.), from N. & C. Greece and S. Albania, usually on serpentine, is similar to {\b 19} but has rather stout stolons 1·5-4·5 cm, bearing crown of leaves, more robust stems up to 40 cm, and a longer fruiting raceme. It is probably not specifically distinct from {\b 19}.
